<br>
Mages are missing a number of tools in the charm book of tricks.  Namely, root, stun, and a way to take damage for a short period of time (rune).  This will hurt.<br>
<br>
However, charming outdoors should be perfectly doable.<br>
<br>
First, you can try charm-kiting techniques (which rely on faster footspeed than your targets).  I never got much into this, so go ask a bard.  =)<br>
<br>
Second, you can charm-duel.  Charm a pet, and sick it on another mob.  Toss a damage shield on your pet if your pet is weaker than the target mob.<br>
<br>
Now, back the hell up.  You want to be just beyond max mez range.<br>
<br>
When charm breaks, either recharm if the mobs run slow, or mez -- hopefully you get both mez's off before they get to you.<br>
<br>
But now, your lack of root sucks.  Typically, you'd root one mob, and sick the other mob on it until it regained aggro.  You'll have to charm one (while mezzed, it works), break mez on the other (small dd), sick your pet on the mob, and start running until your pet regains aggro.<br>
<br>
Now, lets look at a duo case.<br>
<br>
Snare or Root make using a pet MUCH easier.  Root the non-charmed mob, or snare both of them.  Stun also helps.<br>
<br>
Note that the above tactics rely on not having the mobs hit you.  Unless you are in a cramped dungeon, pets should not be actually getting to melee range with you.<br>
<br>
Lastly, note that some classes of mob pet are simply sick.  Get a light blue cleric mob pet, and watch it last forever against whatever mob you choose (nearly impossible to interrupt cheal baby).  Plus, casting mobs tend to stop and cast a spell while running after you -- a perfect time to get in a mez or a recharm.<br>
<br>
None of these tactics are as easy as simply summoning a pet.  However, the end result is 1 dead and 1 heavily injured mob, which you can then finish off for double xp.  The charmed mob doesn't have to match your pets DPS -- the SUM of both the charmed mob and the mob you are attacking have to match your pets DPS.<br>
