<br>
Pet only spells do work on charmed pets, as evidenced by Beastlords using Puppet Strings to charm a mob then casting their pet buff on it. Also, there was a time when an enchanter could kill summoned mobs like imps and elementals by charming them and casting reclaim energy on 'em.<br>
<br>
It is also quite possible to haste charmed pets and make 'em DW if you <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> really</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> know what you're doing. Generally it's a good tactic to charm where you can't get hit. Examples I've done include Spectres in Oasis and finishing off lvl 48 in Dreadlands. If a mob never hits you, there's no worry about it tearing you to shreds when charm breaks. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
However, as mentioned, a magician couldn't pull all of the tricks. I wouldn't expect a magician to be able to live long keeping Optio Crassa as a pet in Seru (summons, comes with his own second weapon, quads for 175), while I can (though I still die a lot).<br>
<br>
I generally don't see magicians <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> wanting</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to use charm solo either; my previous soloing grounds, Fungusbeats in FG, I could only get about a yellow per hour despite frequently having <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> two</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> hasted mobs quadding for 130+ in camp in fairly tight quarters, while an epic magician could match or exceed the experience gain <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> much</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> more safely. Charm for a magician would really only be powerful in a group setting.<br>
<br>
